#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:352
#, no-c-format
msgid "Security best practice for SCAP Workbench"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:353
#, no-c-format
msgid "As a security best practice, avoid installing application software such as SCAP Workbench on the target system that you plan to harden. Instead, install SCAP Workbench on a client machine and apply the hardening on the target system, while maintaining an air gap before the target system is connected to a potentially insecure network."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:362
#, no-c-format
msgid "What are the key components of the SCAP framework?"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid "SCAP consists of the following important components, which interact with each other:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Open Vulnerability and Assessment Language (OVAL)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:372
#, no-c-format
msgid "An XML format for testing the presence of a specific state."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:378
#, no-c-format
msgid "Extensible Configuration Checklist Description Format (XCCDF)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:380
#, no-c-format
msgid "An XML format that specifies security checklists, benchmarks and configuration documentation. The XCCDF file includes a benchmark as a set of different profiles related to different groups. Each group is a set of rules that has OVAL definitions. Each profile is related to different good practices such as &stiga;, &hipaaa;, &pcidssa;, or ANSSI."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:390
#, no-c-format
msgid "Common Platform Enumeration (CPE)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:392
#, no-c-format
msgid "A structured naming scheme to identify information technology systems, platforms and software packages. It is maintained by NIST and NDV. The naming scheme consists of the following elements: <literal>cpe:/<replaceable>part</replaceable>:<replaceable>vendor</replaceable>:<replaceable>product</replaceable>:<replaceable>version</replaceable>:<replaceable>update</replaceable>:<replaceable>edition</replaceable>:<replaceable>language</replaceable></literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:401
#, no-c-format
msgid "DataStreams (DS)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:403
#, no-c-format
msgid "An XML format that packs different SCAP components (CPE, XCCDF, OVAL) into a single file. It can be used to distribute SCAP content over the network. The DataStreams files are useful because they include everything you need when you want to harden and audit your &suselinux; system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:412
#, no-c-format
msgid "Common Configuration Enumeration (CCE)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:414
#, no-c-format
msgid "Unique identifiers for security-related system configuration issues."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:422
#, no-c-format
msgid "&ssg; content and directories"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:424
#, no-c-format
msgid "&suse; ships the SSG toolset in the <package>scap-security-guide</package> package. It contains the latest set of security policies for Linux systems. The <literal>&ssg;</literal> is maintained upstream in the <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/ComplianceAsCode/\">ComplianceAsCode</link> repository."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:431
#, no-c-format
msgid "After you have installed the package, the SSG security content and the related files are available in your system from the following directories:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:437
#, no-c-format
msgid "Overview of files and directories"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/usr/share/xml/scap/ssg/content/</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:442
#, no-c-format
msgid "Contains the SSG security content. It consists of several <xref linkend=\"openscap-components\" xrefstyle=\"select:title\"/> , which are all based on XML. All XML files in that directory are named according to the SCAP component and to the product they apply to."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:448
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can view all available security policies by getting a list of datastream files:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: article_openscap.xml:451
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;<command>ls -l /usr/share/xml/scap/ssg/content/ssg-*-ds.xml</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:455
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/usr/share/doc/scap-security-guide/guides/</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:457
#, no-c-format
msgid "Contains profiles for different hardening policies in a human-readable format. They describe the profiles that are included in the DataStream files. Each profile is a guide on securing your operating system to ensure compliance with a regulation."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:462
#, no-c-format
msgid "The guides usually have the following structure:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:467
#, no-c-format
msgid "Short description"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:472
#, no-c-format
msgid "Profile title. For example: <citetitle>&disaa; &stiga; for &productname; &product-ga;</citetitle>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:478
#, no-c-format
msgid "Profile ID. For example: <citetitle>xccdf_org.ssgproject.content_profile_stig</citetitle>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:484
#, no-c-format
msgid "Revision history. Information about the current version and status of the profile. For example: <citetitle>xccdf_org.ssgproject.content_profile_stig</citetitle>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:491
#, no-c-format
msgid "Platforms (in CPE notation). Lists the products or systems to which the profile applies. For example: <citetitle>cpe:/o:suse:linux_enterprise_server:15</citetitle>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:498
#, no-c-format
msgid "A table of contents"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:503
#, no-c-format
msgid "A checklist that consists of groups (and subgroups) with rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:506
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each rule consists of a short description, the rationale behind the rule, a severity (low, medium or high) and a unique identifier in the <literal>Common Configuration Enumeration (CCE)</literal> format. The CCE number for each rule is provided to &suse; by NIST."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:512
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each rule also lists references to different good practices. For example, the rule known by the unique identifier <literal>CCE-83289-9</literal> in &stiga; has a reference to a specific good practice <literal>A.12.4.1</literal> in ISO/IEC 27001:2013."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid "If remediation options exist for a rule, they are listed in different formats."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: article_openscap.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid "<filename>/usr/share/scap-security-guide</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:528
#, no-c-format
msgid "Contains subdirectories with fix scripts that can be used to remediate the target system in case a vulnerability is found during a scan. Fix scripts are available in the following two formats: Shell scripts ( <filename>bash/<replaceable>*.sh</replaceable></filename> ) and &ansible; snippets ( <filename>ansible/<replaceable>*.yml</replaceable></filename> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:541
#, no-c-format
msgid "&ssg; profiles"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:542
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>&ssg;</literal> contains multiple profiles. The applicable profiles are specific to the individual product and its underlying development stream."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:546
#, no-c-format
msgid "They are maintained and hosted in the following repository: <link xlink:href=\"https://github.com/ComplianceAsCode/content/tree/master/products/sle15/profiles\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:550
#, no-c-format
msgid "After the installation of the <package>scap-security-guide</package> package, human-readable versions of the profiles are available in your file system in <filename>/usr/share/doc/scap-security-guide/guides</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:555
#, no-c-format
msgid "To list the guides for each profile in an HTML format, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: article_openscap.xml:558
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;<command>ls -l /usr/share/doc/scap-security-guide/guides/ssg*.html</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:559
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can then see the guide related to a specific profile in your Web browser. For example, to see the &productnameshort; &product-ga; &stiga; profile using the Mozilla Firefox Web browser, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: article_openscap.xml:564
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;<command>firefox\n"
      "/usr/share/doc/scap-security-guide/guides/ssg-sle15-guide-stig.html</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid "Alternatively, find the same content online as static HTML pages: <link xlink:href=\"https://complianceascode.github.io/content-pages/guides/index.html\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:570
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the online versions, scroll to the appropriate product and select one of the available profiles."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:575
#, no-c-format
msgid "Viewing information on SSG profiles"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:576
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each security policy can have multiple profiles, which provide policies implemented according to specific security baselines. Every profile can select different rules and use different values. You can list these profiles using the following command format:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: article_openscap.xml:581
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;<command>oscap info --fetch-remote-resources\n"
      "/usr/share/xml/scap/ssg/content/ssg-<replaceable>OPERATING-SYSTEM</replaceable>-<replaceable>TYPE-OF-FILE</replaceable>.xml</command><co xml:id=\"ssg-profiles-info-view\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:586
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the above command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:591
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace <replaceable>OPERATING-SYSTEM</replaceable> with <literal>sle15</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:596
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace <replaceable>TYPE-OF-FILE</replaceable> with either <literal>ds</literal> or <literal>xccdf</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:604
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, you can view information about the <literal>ds</literal> files of &productnameshort; &product-ga; using the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: article_openscap.xml:608
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user;<command>oscap info\n"
      "/usr/share/xml/scap/ssg/content/ssg-sle15-ds.xml</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:610
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following technical terms appear in the <command>oscap info</command> output for <literal>ds</literal> and <literal>xccdf</literal> files:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:617
#, no-c-format
msgid "Document type"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:618
#, no-c-format
msgid "Describes the file format. Common types include XCCDF, OVAL, Source Data Stream and Result Data Stream."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:626
#, no-c-format
msgid "Checklist version"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:627
#, no-c-format
msgid "The XCCDF version only shown for XCCDF files. Common values are <literal>1.1</literal> and <literal>1.2</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:635
#, no-c-format
msgid "Imported"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:636
#, no-c-format
msgid "The date the file was imported for use with &openscap;. As &openscap; uses the local file system and has no proprietary database format, the imported date is the same as the file modification date."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:645
#, no-c-format
msgid "Status"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: article_openscap.xml:646
#, no-c-format
msgid "The XCCDF Benchmark status. Common values include <literal>accepted</literal> , <literal>draft</literal> , <literal>deprecated</literal> , and <literal>incomplete</literal> . Please refer to the XCCDF specification for details. This is only shown for XCCDF files."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: article_openscap.xml:656
#, no-c-format
msgid "Generated"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
